data.name: Catwalk
data.description:
A walkable catwalk must give access to technical systems and installations in the roof, without need for specialist safety equipment or training/qualifications. Including:

- Floodlighting system distribution

- Tactical and other broadcast cameras

- Telecoms systems

- Audio systems

- Flags (unless otherwise mounted on motorized winches)

- Goal Line Technology

data.name: Building Management System (BMS) Control Room
data.description: A modern and integrated electronic BMS system, with direct control of all critical building services, with main/primary control and terminal within the Venue Operations Centre (8.2).

data.name: Power compound / room
data.description:
Dedicated, secured spaces must be provided for Stadium and Venue generators, and/or Uninterruptible Power supplies, overlay electrical distribution equipment and major cabling.

Venue generators may be temporary or permanent, for primary power purposes (where utility is not available or adequate), and/or redundant back-up. Adequate space for machine footprint, maintenance access, exhaust/ventilation, air intake, fuel storage and refuelling access, plus associated control equipment, distribution and cabling.

Compounds for temporary equipment must to allow for easy installation, maintenance access, and be accessible for refuelling (within 30m of a roadway suitable for tankers).

data.name: Floodlights
data.description:
A pitch illuminance system must be provided, which meets all requirements detailed in the FIFA Lighting Standards and Guide.

The baseline requirement is FIFA Standard A for the Final Stadium, and Standard B for other stadiums - unless any alterations or exceptions are specified/agreed by FIFA.

Compliance of system designs, and complete systems must be independently tested according to the methodology detailed in the FIFA Lighting Guide, with results provided to FIFA.

Any new systems installed for FWC are expected to be LED, with centralised electronic control.

data.name: Wind Measurement Equipment
data.description:
Anemometers placed as necessary around stadium permanent and temporary structures (particularly seating stands) with live measurements streamed to the BMS (or otherwise to the VOC) in real time.

Automated warnings should be set when relevant defined thresholds are approached, or exceeded which could affect venue operations (e.g. require evacuation of a stand)

data.name: Cable Pathways
data.description:
Cable pathways with segregated routes for all broadcast / ICT / power cabling (and other services as necessary) must be provided around the stadium and precinct, including suitable containment measures provided wherever necessary to support and protect the occupying cable.

Adequate space must be allocated to ensure that different services remain segregated, adequately separated from each other and surrounding environment, are adequately supported and mechanically protected, and can be installed rapidly and continuously. For example without need to remove end connectors, or 'thread' unless absolutely necessary. It should be assumed that power cabling must be laid flat, and cannot be stacked.

data.name: Passenger Lifts
data.description:
Passenger lifts must be separately available and dedicated to all different user groups and functional areas which require them, including meeting all accessibility requirements. For example:

VVIP / VIP

Hospitality

General Spectators

Broadcast & Media

Operational areas

The entrance of the lift has to have a width of at least 100cm

Consider accessibility needs for disabled people and people with limited mobility

The entrance of the lift has to have a width of at least between 90cm - 120cm

data.name: Service Lifts
data.description:
Service lifts must be provided separately to passenger lifts, to all areas required within stadiums.

Depending on local regulations, it may be necessary to provide separate 'clean' and 'dirty' lifts for food delivery and waste collection.

Cable Bridge/Trench/Tunnel
data.description:
A network of cable paths must be provided around the venue, interconnecting locations including the broadcast compound, the pitch, camera positions, the tribune and commentary areas, CCR, studios/presentation platforms, mixed zone, control rooms and locations, CCFs, and TER (and others as needed). While routes should be shared, segregated constituent pathways must be provided for broadcast / ICT / power cabling, and other technical services as necessary. Segregated services should be well-supported, protected from mechanical or other relevant risks, and presented as continuously open pathways.

Wherever a physical barrier, roadway or major pedestrian flow must be crossed, or where contained cabling may be at risk from outside influence, appropriate containment measures must be provided. For example, hooks, trays, catenary wire crossings, barriers and bump-stops, horizontal and vertical penetrations (to allow for installation without removal of terminations), conduits, trenches, yellow jacket type cable trays, cable ramps/ladders/steps, risers, tunnels or bridges. The simplest solution providing adequate support, protection and access is preferred..
